"Impaired rectal sensation","Valsalva-pelvic floor incoordination","Reduced intestinal motility","Sphincter hypertonicity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of infant dyschezia is \u003Cstrong\u003Evalsalva-pelvic floor incoordination\u003C/strong\u003E. Infants have difficulty coordinating the increase in intra-abdominal pressure (Valsalva maneuver) with pelvic floor relaxation needed for successful defecation. This Valsalva-pelvic floor incoordination leads to distress during defecation despite normal stool consistency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed colonic transit time\u003C/strong\u003E - Transit time is normal in dyschezia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired rectal sensation\u003C/strong\u003E - Rectal sensation is intact in dyschezia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced intestinal motility\u003C/strong\u003E - Intestinal motility is normal in dyschezia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESphincter hypertonicity\u003C/strong\u003E - The issue is coordination rather than muscle tone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition typically resolves spontaneously as the infant develops better coordination between abdominal and pelvic floor muscles during defecation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Infant dyschezia occurs due to poor coordination between abdominal pressure and pelvic floor relaxation.","The condition typically resolves spontaneously as the infant learns to coordinate defecation muscles.","Valsalva maneuver must be coordinated with pelvic floor relaxation for successful defecation."],"references":["Kramer EA, den Hertog-Kuijl JH, van den Broek LM, van Leengoed E, Bulk AM, Kneepkens CM, Benninga MA. Defecation patterns in infants: a prospective cohort study. Arch Dis Child. 2015 Jun;100(6):533-6. doi: 10.1136/archdischild-2014-307448. Epub 2014 Dec 24. PMID: 25539766.","Pawasarat A, Biank VF. Constipation in Pediatrics: A Clinical Review. Pediatr Ann. 2021 Aug;50(8):e320-e324. doi: 10.3928/19382359-20210714-01. Epub 2021 Aug 1. PMID: 34398719.","Kadim M, Putri UM, Gunardi H, Wulandari HF, Wahidiyat PA, Pardede SO, Indawati W. Prevalence, Risk Factors, and Pediatrician Awareness of Infant Dyschezia in Indonesia. Pediatr Gastroenterol Hepatol Nutr. 2023 Mar;26(2):116-126. doi: 10.5223/pghn.2023.26.2.116. Epub 2023 Mar 7. PMID: 36950058; PMCID: PMC10025572."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71348"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15345"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71348"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-25T22:43:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-25T22:44:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8036"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87090"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{